<TEXT>
more than tax increases and spending cuts are 
at stake in the nearly roundtheclock deficitreduction 
negotiations between congressional and bush administration 
officials 
as they struggle to avert wholesale cuts in federal programs 
next month the presidents aides and top members of congress also 
must decide how to divide targeted tax cuts that would cost more 
than 20 billion over the next five years the intended 
beneficiaries include rich investors giant corporations 
firsttime homebuyers and workers pursuing employerfinanced 
educations 
most of a dozen tax benefits that expire this year enjoy wide 
support in congress and are backed by the administration thus 
their renewal is likely to be attached to any deficit package 
approved by the negotiators that package likely will be the only 
tax bill passed this year 
the fate of another big proposed tax cut one that has been the 
subject of a running battle between congress and president bush 
since he took office is far less certain the administration 
insists on including in the package a cut in the tax on capital 
gains but democratic leaders are saying that cant be done unless 
overall income tax rates on upperincome americans are raised to 
pay for it 
senate republican negotiators on friday reacted angrily to 
implications that their party is trying to favor the rich that 
is the old democrat lie that has been out here for 20 30 40 
years said gop leader bob dole of kansas 
his anger was prompted by disclosure of an analysis showing that 
a package of tax increases offered by republicans would lopsidedly 
favor higherincome americans chiefly because nearly 80 percent 
of the benefit of a capital gains reduction would go to those with 
incomes over 100000 a year 
negotiators apparently had little success in another day of 
closeddoor meetings friday at nearby andrews air force base in 
maryland they will try again sunday hoping for quick agreement 
but promising nothing 
as far as progress is concerned griped sen pete domenici 
rnm were nowhere 
the goal of the talks is a plan to slash 50 billion from the 
budget deficit during the 12 months that begin oct 1 plus another 
450 billion in the following four years without an agreement the 
grammrudman deficitreduction law will be triggered forcing 100 
billion in cuts in most federal programs 
but while most of the government is focused on the need to rein 
in spending the budget negotiators have their eyes on renewing 
several tax breaks that otherwise would die this year 
the biggest special benefit likely to be added to the 
antideficit package is supported by bush and most members of 
congress it would cut business taxes by more than 92 billion 
over the next five years by renewing a credit and deduction rules 
aimed at increasing investment in research and experimentation 
another 37 billion would go to investors who build or 
rehabilitate rental housing available for lowincome people 
among other expiring tax breaks that are likely to be renewed a 
14 billion credit for part of the wages employers pay newly hired 
lowincome workers a 17 billion exclusion for a limited amount 
ot tuition that employers pay for workers a 546 million exclusion 
for employerfinanced legal aid for workers a 770 million subsidy 
for lowerincome people buying a first home and a 18 billion 
credit to help selfemployed people pay for health insurance 
