the us military is handing out 
radios and more newspapers to gis hungry for news but its not 
printing or broadcasting anything the strictly moslem government 
could deem religious or racy 
in the early weeks of the deployment troops often asked 
visitors to send copies of local newspapers saying they knew 
little about their mission or the situation back home 
operation desert shield since has spawned two new newspapers 
the desert defender and the desert dragon as well as several more 
informal newsletters 
the military this week distributed portable radios by the dozens 
at base camps so the troops can hear armed forces radio and local 
englishlanguage broadcasts 
the radios were distributed after the military refined 
programming to make sure none of the broadcasts include religious 
programming or gospel music 
we are being very sensitive to the culture of the host 
country army col rick kiernan said we want to get the troops 
music information and sports programming but we also want to be 
good guests 
a transmitter was recently installed in saudi arabia to relay 
the radio and armed force television also is available in some 
areas where us troops are housed in military housing or hotels 
television programming includes sports news and other shows 
transmitted under agreements with the us cable news network espn 
and the major television networks 
the air force published the first issue of the weekly desert 
defender last week and issued no 2 a few days ago 
most of the editorial material is written by air force public 
affairs personnel included on the front page of the second issue 
was the text of president bushs aug 30 address to the troops 
also on the front page is a photograph of the f117a stealth 
fighter which reporters have been asking to see for several weeks 
the paper also contains comics and a crossword puzzle 
