<TEXT>
asian refugees heading home from kuwait are 
finding more strife in the desert even after being moved from a 
nightmare camp on the iraqi border 
relief officials closed the squalid shaalan i border camp on 
thursday and transferred about 5000 indians to an organized tent 
city near azraq 50 miles east of the capital amman 
but 14 hours after arriving on a barren windswept slope most 
of them had gone unfed and on friday they appeared worried about 
their future 
this morning we are eating only dust said jose daniel as 
the constant wind blew clouds of ochrecolored powder across the 
camp situated on a field of lava rocks 
the red cross which built the azraq i camp distributed 
sandwiches bread fruit and vegetables a couple of hours later 
but that did little to relieve the uncertainty and bewilderment 
among the refugees 
we thought we were going to amman they brought us here in the 
night said pa abraham who was among the indians bused from 
shaalan i 
he and others said they had left cooking utensils and some food 
behind at the border camp 160 miles away 
they told us we would have everything we left all our things 
behind so as not to carry extra luggage said achuthan sreekumar 
compared with shaalan i a haphazard collection of makeshift 
tents that sprang up on the border after iraqs aug 2 invasion of 
kuwait azraq i is a model camp 
shaalan is population swelled to as many as 50000 indians 
bangladeshis pakistanis sri lankans and filipinos 
many were stranded for up to two weeks with little food and 
water and no bathroom facilities in a desert where temperatures 
soared to 120 degrees during the day and dropped to 60 degrees or 
lower at night 
as relief efforts became betterorganized and more aid was 
supplied to jordans government those awaiting transportation home 
from jordan were moved to two other border camps and two near 
azraq 
a highpressure water line from amman to azraq was tapped for 
the camp so water was plentiful electricity was to be hooked up 
