shuttle columbia began early today after nasa checked and rechecked 
for hydrogen leaks that halted two earlier launch attempts 
columbia was scheduled to lift off with seven astronauts and an 
astronomical observatory at 128 am edt tuesday 
the space agency replaced a temperature sensor after a helium 
test found a slight leak thursday said bascom murrah in charge of 
prelaunch operations the sensor about the size of a spark plug 
is on a fuel line leading to one of three main engines in the rear 
compartment 
a final check produced no further leaks murrah said 
earlier in the week workers replaced a crushed seal on a fuel 
valve engineers believe hydrogen entered columbias rear 
compartment around the seal during fueling for the first launch 
attempt in may and one last week 
murrah said he was more confident than he has been for months 
until this week we were shotgunning it we were going at the 
thing even if we didnt know it was leaking murrah said we 
have found two definite leaks to me that says weve actually 
found something and fixed it 
the true test will come when more than a halfmillion gallons of 
liquid hydrogen and liquid oxygen are pumped into columbia on 
monday none of the other countdowns have made it past that point 
time quickly is running out for the astronomy mission nasa will 
try for a few days to launch columbia before turning its attention 
to discovery which must lift off with a sun probe by oct 23 or 
face a 13month delay 
discovery is the only shuttle in which hydrogen leaks have not 
been found it was the last shuttle to fly carrying the flawed 
hubble space telescope into orbit in april atlantis was grounded 
in june 
columbias astronauts return to kennedy space center this 
weekend for another try at getting off the ground four of them are 
astronomers who will operate the 150 million observatory called 
astro 
astros three ultraviolet telescopes and one xray telescope 
will observe more than 260 highenergy objects some of them 
millions of degrees problems with the xray telescope forced nasa 
to halt columbias second countdown late last month 
the observatory will remain in columbias cargo bay throughout 
the nineto 10day mission 
