<TEXT>
nasas fourth countdown for columbia 
began saturday as scientists prepared once again for the long 
astronomy mission and tried to keep their excitement in check 
columbia has been grounded for 3 months because of leaking 
hydrogen officials will not know for sure whether all of the leaks 
have been plugged until the shuttle is fueled for tuesdays early 
morning launch 
this is the fourth countdown were going through were 
getting a little bit too used to it said mission scientist ted 
gull but the nervousness of the first flight isnt there we 
know were ready and thats a very positive thing to say 
since the last launch attempt 1 weeks ago nasa has replaced 
two leaking components in columbias aft compartment a new set of 
recirculation pumps also was installed but engineers later 
determined there was nothing wrong with the ones that were removed 
hydrogen flooded columbias aft compartment during fueling for 
the sept 6 launch attempt but no leaks were detected around new 
fuel lines between the orbiter and external tank the site of 
extensive leaking during fueling for the first launch attempt in 
late may 
columbias second countdown was halted late last month after 
communication with one of four telescopes aboard the shuttle was 
disrupted the telescopes constitute a 150 million observatory 
called astro that will probe ultraviolet light and xrays emitted 
from some of the hottest objects in the universe 
gull and other scientists have had to revise astros observing 
schedule after each launch delay the mission originally was 
scheduled for march 1986 but was put on indefinite hold when 
challenger exploded earlier that year 
only three or four targets were lost as a result of the latest 
12day postponement gull said among the more than 260 objects 
astro is set to observe are a comet making its first recorded pass 
through the solar system a supernova and jupiter 
four astronomers who are part of columbias sevenman crew will 
operate astros three ultraviolet telescopes roundtheclock the 
xray telescope will be managed by computer commands sent from the 
ground 
the observatory will remain in the shuttles cargo bay 
throughout the nineto10day mission the first in five years 
devoted entirely to scientific research 
theres guarded excitement gull said i think its about 
time astro deserves success nasa deserves a success too 
nasa has not launched a shuttle since april when discovery 
carried the hubble space telescope into orbit two months later 
the 15 billion telescope was found to have a badly flawed mirror 
that blurs images 
launch director bob sieck said columbia will have two chances to 
lift off tuesday and wednesday if it isnt launched by then its 
mission will be postponed until after discoverys october mission 
to deploy a sunprobing satellite 
discovery must lift off by oct 23 or wait until late 1991 when 
earth is in proper alignment again with the sun and jupiter the 
satellite called ulysses needs jupiters gravity to achieve the 
right solar orbit 
gull already is mapping out an observing schedule for november 
in case columbia does not get off the ground this week 
were trying to hedge our bets he said 
