a killer who shot and stabbed two hikers as they slept in a remote 
shelter on the appalachian trail hikers were warned to stay off 
the trail in pennsylvania murders are very rare on the trail 
but we cant outguess somebody that is a murderer so were taking 
precautions said brian king spokesman for the appalachian trail 
conference 
geoffrey logan hood 26 of signal mountain tenn and molly 
larue 25 of shaker heights ohio were found dead thursday by two 
other hikers hood was shot and ms larue was stabbed repeatedly 
said state trooper rodney anderson both apparently were slain as 
they slept in the cove mountain leanto shelter 
they were caught off guard and somebody attacked them 
sometime before dawn said perry county coroner michael j 
shalonis he said the couple had been dead 12 to 16 hours when they 
were found 
police combed the area on foot and in helicopters saturday 
were not assuming anything said state police cpl brady 
williams when asked whether the killer was thought to be in the 
area police said they did not have any suspects 
the appalachian trail conference which maintains the 2140mile 
trail sent out handbills to be posted in a 30mile area 
surrounding the shelter the site is about three miles southeast of 
duncannon a rural town 15 miles northwest of harrisburg 
the national park service warns appalachian trail hikers to 
exercise appropriate caution including temporarily bypassing the 
appalachian trail in pennsylvania the sign warns 
the pennsylvania portion of the trail extends for 230 miles from 
penmar md to the delaware water gap at the new jersey line 
more than 3 million people hike along the appalachian trail 
which runs from maine to georgia the pennsylvania segment is one 
of the most heavily traveled according to the conference based in 
harpers ferry wva 
