thousands of canadian auto workers went on strike 
saturday against ford motor co of canada as negotiators resumed 
talks aimed at settling the dispute over pay benefits and job 
security 
parallel talks continued saturday in the united states between 
the united auto workers and general motors corp after negotiators 
in detroit agreed to extend a midnight strike deadline 
the uaw told its members not to strike while negotiators worked 
to reach a new threeyear agreement covering 300000 gm workers 
nationwide 
the strike in canada wont affect production until monday 
because ford of canada plants do not operate weekends 
up to 12800 workers were expected to walk off the job at nine 
plants and two offices in ontario the company has two plants in 
oakville five in windsor one in st thomas and one in niagara 
falls 
the canadian auto workers union called the strike the first 
against ford since 1976 after negotiators failed to meet a friday 
midnight deadline for reaching agreement on a new contract 
negotiators for both sides met formally and informally saturday 
at a toronto hotel they were to hold a formal negotiating session 
on sunday morning 
the process is continuing on both sides ford spokesman jim 
hartford said we are experiencing a strike were doing our best 
to ensure its a short one 
union spokeswoman peggy nash said there were still many 
unresolved issues separating both sides 
it sounds like the two sides are still very far apart ford 
negotiator don mckenzie said he was still optimistic this could be 
sorted out quickly she said union president bob white 
didnt seem so optimistic 
the unions contract with ford expired on friday 
everybody is pretty much ready for this windsor autoworker 
tom bellmore said after saturdays strike announcement everybody 
is resigned that this is the way its got to be 
like many of his fellow workers bellmore said he had stocked up 
on groceries and other supplies in preparation for the shutdown 
both sides have refused to disclose details of their proposals 
and demands the union is seeking higher wages including money to 
help offset a proposed federal goods and services tax better 
benefits and more time off white said the average hourly base pay 
now is about 15 
white said progress has been made on job security and mckenzie 
conceded that money is the main problem 
the union rejected the companys initial offer on wednesday the 
union made its proposal on friday but the company has yet to 
respond white said 
in detroit the uaw and general motors agreed to extend their 
national labor contract past its friday expiration date and talks 
continued saturday 
both sides have refused to disclose the progress of the 
negotiations but aspects of job security and benefits for gm 
workers remain unresolved 
in both countries the auto workers unions target one company in 
their talks in hopes of fashioning a pattern contract for workers 
at other automakers 
