a jury has awarded 136 million to auto racing 
promoters who sued a newspaper for libel over articles about the 
cleveland grand prix 
the case stemmed from articles written by reporter gary webb for 
the cleveland plain dealer primarily in 1984 and also in 1985 and 
1986 
the eightmember jury returned the finding friday on the second 
day of deliberations 
alex machaskee publisher of the plain dealer said the 
newspaper intends to appeal 
the plaintiffs were charles k newcomb and james h foster 
along with the company ck newcomb and associates they promoted 
the indystyle car race at burke lakefront airport starting in 
1982 when the event was called the budweiser cleveland 500 
the company newcomb and foster sought 6 million in 
compensatory damages and 10 million in punitive damages in the 
suit filed in 1985 
the plaintiffs lawyer jerome s kalur could not be reached 
for comment he was not at his office and has no residential phone 
listing newcomb also has no listing foster was not at his 
residence according to a recorded message 
in 1984 a week before the 1984 budweiser cleveland grand prix 
the plain dealer reported that newcomb and foster paid themselves 
nearly 1 million from race proceeds in violation of a lease with 
the city newcomb and foster declined to be interviewed for that 
story 
the newspaper also said the race did not satisfy rent payments 
to the city because newcomb and foster told the city the race was 
deeply in debt 
lawyers for the plain dealer argued during the eightweek trial 
before cuyahoga county common pleas judge joseph f mcmanamon that 
the primary points of the articles were indisputably true 
but lawyers for the plaintiffs argued the race in fact lost 
money its first two years and that the articles were false 
newcomb and foster sold the rights to the race in march 1985 to 
businessman and former race car driver roger penske and the plain 
dealer later became cosponsor of the event 
mcmanamon said the jury awarded ck newcomb and associates 22 
million in compensatory damages and 2 million in punitive damages 
newcomb 2 million compensatory and 35 million punitive and 
foster 400000 compensatory and 35 million punitive 
