<TEXT>
the united auto workers union and general motors 
corp recessed talks early saturday on a national labor contract 
and the union told its members not to strike 
negotiators had faced a midnight strike deadline talks were to 
resume saturday morning on a threeyear contract for about 300000 
active gm workers in 29 states the contract would serve as a model 
for talks with other major automakers 
gm thinks that meaningful progress has been made in the 
current contract negotiations and that an agreement will be 
reached said a statement issued by gm vice president alfred s 
warren jr negotiators will continue efforts to achieve this 
goal 
the latest bargaining session ended about 1220 am 
we are continuing our efforts to reach a settlement uaw 
vice president stephen yokich said in a statement released about 
1045 pm uawrepresented workers have been advised to stay on 
the job and report for work on their regular shift until further 
notice 
only gms bowling green ky assembly plant which makes 
corvettes was scheduled for production during the weekend the 
companys other 30 car and truck assembly plants are idle on 
weekends 
the uaws contracts with gm ford and chrysler corp expired at 
midnight they cover more than 450000 active auto workers in the 
united states and wallaceburg ontario 
in toronto the canadian auto workers called a strike friday 
against ford motor cos canadian subsidiary after negotiators did 
not meet a midnight deadline negotiators had reported talks were 
progressing and bargaining was to resume saturday ford plants in 
canada are closed weekends 
it was the first ford canada strike since 1976 the caw 
represents about 12800 ford workers 
the canadian workers make a variety of components for fords 
us assembly plants a strike in canada would likely affect the 
companys us operations within a week 
in the united states the uaw chose on aug 28 to focus its 
bargaining on gm talks with ford and chrysler have been put on 
hold since uaw leaders have said they plan to use a contract 
ratified by gm workers as a pattern for agreements at ford and 
chrysler 
as the talks entered their final hours unresolved issues 
included job security wages and pensions union leaders contacted 
friday said they were not told details about the unresolved issues 
tentative agreements had been reached on a variety of mostly 
noneconomic issues including health safety and attendance policy 
dramatic changes in the auto industry during the 1980s 
especially the growth of japanese automakers shares of the us 
car and truck market have affected labor relations between the uaw 
and the big three in general and gm specifically 
the big threes collective market share dropped about 6 
percentage points during the decade to about 68 percent last year 
during the same time the japanese companies share rose by about 
the same amount to over 25 percent 
that has forced gm ford and chrysler to shrink their operations 
and their work forces in response the uaws primary emphasis has 
shifted to job security from wage increases 
as the companies worked to cut costs they adopted a parts 
delivery system called justintime under such a scheme 
automakers ship parts and component systems to assembly plants just 
before they are needed sometimes within hours of installation 
at the same time automakers consolidated manufacturing to 
reduce redundancies and expenses 
that opened a new strategy for the uaw one whose effects were 
shown last month 
because of justintime delivery the uaw can shut down assembly 
plants some of which have more than 5000 workers by striking a 
critical parts plant that employs far fewer people 
last month the uaw struck gms ac rochester west parts plant in 
flint for six days over local issues including an employment level 
guarantee before the walkout ended gm was forced to close seven 
assembly plants because of parts shortages those shutdowns in 
turn resulted in layoffs at other component plants 
</TEXT>
